title: For Sale/Trade:  SINO-SOVIET SKSs TYPE 56 CHROME LINE BARREL
postcontent:
1956 /26\ Jianshe Arsenal SKSs for sale. Sino-Soviet Type 56s were the rifles that were built under Russian supervision when China adopted the SKS as their main service rifle in 1956. These rifles have Russian barrel proofs and very low serial numbers. 140 thousands. There were at least a million of these rifles made per year all the way up until 1980. In 1973, you began to see less material used for these rifles. Pinned barrels, no barrel lugs, spike bayonet, etc. These rifles were built exactly from Russian specs and have Russian proofs. Could be Russian barrels. This rifle is also known as "ghost 26"'s meaning that they did not stamp with a arsenal code. Very few rifles were like these in the early stages of manufacture. Pretty interesting. 

It has a little cosmoline left in them and have NOT been shot by me. The bore is excellent. Extremely crisp. The stock has typical wear from being in a crate for most of it's life time and there is light pitting in a spot on the receiver but it is only exterior and nothing serious. It is to be expected with military surplus guns. The bluing on it is fantastic. Better than most I have seen come out of this time period. 

I am looking to get 325.

 I can ship to a FFL01 or 03. 

You can email me or text at fourfourthree ninesevenfive sixsevenfivenine

title: For Sale:  STEYR Model 1912 9MM Largo Automatic Pistole (NOT 9mm LUGER but convertable to 9mm luger)
postcontent:
Steyr 1912 9mm Largo ( long ) automatic Pistol also know as the model 1914 as the Austrian Army Adopted it that year.  This one was Manufactured in 1913 so it PRE-DATES Austrian Army Acceptance so it was either a civilian Model OR an ARMY TEST MODEL ! Who Knows? 
       Internally very similar to the COLT 38 Automatic (even the round it shoots is SERIOUSLY SIMILAR to the COLT .38 AUTOMATIC ROUND originally made in 1900!). Ammo is ALWAYS AVAILABLE at Gun Shows as the Spanish LOVED this Cartridge & apparently used it for their Military & Police until the late 1980s LOTS of it around !! They made MILLIONS & MILLIONS of Rounds that are still on the Market !!! Many LLAMA 1911s are Chambered for the 9mm Largo.

 The gun CAN be CONVERTED to 9MM LUGER simply by CHANGING THE BARRELL !! The Germans conscripted  these during WW 2 (as Handguns were in short supply)  and re-Barrelled them in 9MM . The AUSTRIANS just used them as is in WW 2 or so I am told 
 I had thought about  Changing it but the 9MM LARGO Ammo is so CHEAP & AVAILABLE I did NOT!
 The Gun SHOOTS GOOD and is FUN TO SHOOT!. Finish is as you would expect an old gun to be with some pitting here & there and a couple of places where I was told the JEWISH IMPORTER ground off the NAZI MARKINGS that were lightly  stamped  into the Slide . That's UNDERSTANDABLE .  Also One Person suggested that the Scrubb Marks were HUNGARIAN PROOF MARKS that were scrubbed off . WHO KNOWS? The grindings are barely perceptable with your fingers and NOT VERY DEEP! They DON'T hurt the STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY of the GUN!!  It was re-finished after that but it still AIN"T NEW! 


 As I have had several Inquiries about the SERIAL NUMBERS I have added parts of the most Comprehensive email message that I sent. I guess I should have included this info when I posted the Pistole. It took me a LONG TIME to figure out HOW to EDIT the POSTING! 




 UNDERNEATH the Manufacture date of 1913 ( which pre-dates the Austrian Military acceptance ) it also says VEGA  SAC. CA. (ABOVE the MNFR date) and  it says 9MM STEYR  AUSTRIA (underneath the Manufacture Date )which matches the VEGA etc Stamping . The STEYR 1913 is a DEEPER STAMPING and more in line withe the STEYR STAMPINGS that I have seen on other 1912s/1914s is an original Stamping.
 On the Slide's left side under the forward most scrubb mark is stamped Md. 1912 . The serial no. is on the slide is etched in and matches the frame's number . HOWEVER I don't recall WHERE the ORIGINAL Serial No. on the slide is supposed to be,  if there is one at all
  The Barrell's Serial No.  also is etched in and all numbers MATCH. I would suspect that the etched numbers were done to keep the original parts in the same Gun. But of course , I am no expert on the history of what happened to all of these WW1 & WW 2 Guns. I have seen all kinds of things that break all the "expert's " rules ,even on guns that the provenance was IMPECCABLE ( as in guns that I KNEW the old men who BROUGHT THEM BACK from EUROPE in BOTH WARS ! ) !
 There is also on the machined smooth boss between the sight and the clip insertion tower ( which I assume is a boss for mounting a long rang adjustable sight or "VOLLEY SIGHT " on ) some sort of mark that appears to be a very small circle with possibly a crown  or a couple of initials on itop . the crown or inititals point to the right side and are on top of the circle from about 10:30 to 2 o'clock ( if you regard the RIGHT side of the gun as TOP.) If it is initials then the right hand letter ia a "W" . Also it appears that there is either another smaller circle inside the circle or possibly a "C" inside the circle . It is SMALL and that boss seems to have not had as much bluing ( or Browning ,the older finishing method ) on it so it is pitted minutely and masks the "crown" (?) to my eye , even under a Magnifying Glass. But as my moniker in other Gun Sales sites states I am an " OldShooter" so my up close vision sucks.
 Loads from top with Slide Locked Back with  8 round Stripper Clip and is easy to load. INCLUDED is 11 STRIPPER CLIPS for Rapid Reloading if attacked by ZOMBIES en-mass and 5-7 boxes of Ammo . $290

KELTEC KSG SHOTGUN  NEW NICE PUMP SHOTGUN


The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".
This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.
The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.
The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.

title: For Sale/Trade:  your M4 is probably not an M4, please learn the difference
